The analytical performance of the proposed SCN− colorimetric sensor was evaluated under optimal detection conditions. Fig. 3
                        A showed the UV–vis spectra of the ZnPc-AuNSs/ITO electrode after reaction with different concentrations of SCN− solution. It was found that with the increase of SCN− concentration, the absorption peak showed a gradually blue shift from 798 nm to 543 nm. As the concentration of the SCN− varied from 10 nM to 80 mM, the absorbance intensity at 543 nm increased and the absorbance intensity at 798 nm decreased. It is resulted from the reason that the complexing effect of the oxidized AuNSs and SCN− was gradually obvious with the increase of SCN− concentration. The absorption peaks in the UV − vis spectra at 798 and 543 nm represented the AuNSs and AuNPs, respectively. As the SCN− concentration increased, A543nm/A798nm elevated. Accordingly, the ratio of A543nm/A798nm was used to quantify SCN− concentration in this work (Fig. 3B). As shown in Fig. 3B, a non-linear relationship between A543nm/A798nm and SCN− concentration in the range of 10 nM to 80 mM was obtained with a correlation coefficient of 0.9952. The detection limit was 3 nM (3σ). It could be seen that our presented colorimetric sensor showed wider detection range and lower detection limit than most of the other previously reported methods for SCN− determination (Table 1
                        ).
